      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "2b7529d8d30e7aa1",
        "text": "If you are often stuck in a highway traffic jam, instead of passing the time with bagpipe music or poetry readings, you can take a correspondence course: 14 cassettes \"Introduction to Systems Theory \"1 and another 14 cassettes  \"Theory of Society\",2 original recordings of Niklas Luhmann's lectures from 1991/92 and 1992/93. Those who are seldom or never in a traffic jam can now also read the lecture \"Introduction to Systems Theory\". read it again. Dirk Baecker has edited it, with minor corrections to the spoken text and a short index to the central terms. The text edition is recommended for readers who have missed the connection to modern theory development. For they are, not unlike beginners in sociology studies at the time, gently and ambitiously introduced to the theory of social systems, can - unlike in the texts published and authorized by Luhmann himself - follow the theory construction lesson by lesson (\"In today's lesson I will begin with the section on mental and social systems ...\"), and at the end of the lesson sit back, exhausted, with Luhmann's \"Good, that should do for today.\" Or even take a step back,\nbecause \"I don't know if you can quickly come to grips with this confusing theory structure ...\" One thing, however, the reader's re-readers cannot do: ask questions. I wonder if listeners of the time could. The dense, concentrated text argues against it. The master\nmaster himself asked enough questions, for example, where the slip of paper is that says that all the other fifty or sixty thousand slips of paper are wrong."
      },
      "date": 1629286314586
